 to it. First examining these artists in relation to noncoincidence—as silence in poetry, depth in painting, memory in literature, and rhythm in music—she moves through an array of their artworks toward some of Merleau-Ponty’s most exciting themes: our bodily relationship to the world and the dynamic process of expression. She closes with an examination of synesthesia as an intertwining of internal and external realms and a call, finally, for philosophical inquiry as a mode of artistic expression. Structured like a piece of music itself, The Rhythm of Thought offers new contexts in which to approach art, philosophy, and the resonance between them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArt and music. 0aMusic and literature. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th century. 70(DE-601)1061979590(DE-588)4046449-0aPoetik2gnd 70(DE-601)1062214500(DE-588)4040808-5aMusikästhetik2gnd 70(DE-601)1064005410(DE-588)4000626-8aÄsthetik2gnd 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aphenomenology, music, philosophy, aesthetics, poetry, nonfiction, debussy, marcel proust, cezanne, art, paintings, stephane mallarme, masterpiece, silence, depth, memory, rhythm, synesthesia, artistic expression, resonance, harmony, france, creativity, creation, nature, avant-garde, literature, essence, being, movement, voluminousness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022603092040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226031088423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226031088/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles